<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910329-0171</DOCNO><DOCID>910329-0171.</DOCID><HL>   Economy:   Consumer Spending   And Personal Income   Climbed in February</HL><DATE>03/29/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2</SO><IN>ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)U.S. ECONOMIC AND MONETARY INDICATORS (EMI)</IN><LP>   WASHINGTON -- Consumer spending showed a modest rise inFebruary, the Commerce Department said, providing a furthersign that the recession may be bottoming out.   The 0.6% rise was the biggest since September. Spending inJanuary fell 0.6% from the previous month.</LP><TEXT>   Personal income rose 0.2% in February after dropping 0.4%in January.   &quot;The numbers picked up,&quot; said Norman Robertson, chiefeconomist at Mellon Bank in Pittsburgh. But he added theystill &quot;did not pick up a lot of strength.&quot;   The rise in spending brought it to an annual rate of $3.84trillion in February; the rise in income brought it to a$4.736 trillion annual rate.   The Commerce Department said special factors, includingone-time farm-subsidy payments, boosted the income figures inFebruary. Excluding these special factors, personal incomeincreased 0.1%.   The personal savings rate fell slightly to 4.4% ofdisposable income from 4.6% in January.   The figures in the report are adjusted for seasonalchanges.   ---                     PERSONAL INCOME                                                                                                          Here is the Commerce Department's latest report onpersonal income. The figures are at seasonally adjustedannual rates in trillions of dollars.                                                                                                                                      Feb.              Jan.                               1991              1991                                                                                                        Personal income ............  4.736             4.724   Wages and salaries .......  2.742             